<div id="comment_244884083" class="brown_comment">
  <div class="xhr_comment_photo">
    	<a alt="Mike" href="/user/show/7272380-mike"><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1548615999p1/7272380.jpg" alt="7272380" /></a>
  </div>
  <div class="xhr_comment_body">
    <a style="font-weight:bold" href="/user/show/7272380-mike">Mike</a>

      
<span id="freeTextContainer5409561703517888051"><i>s.penkevich wrote: &quot;Mike wrote: &quot;Thanks. For a second there, when you mentioned the postwar thing, my blood ran cold and I reached with a trembling ha</i></span>
  <span id="freeText5409561703517888051" style="display:none"><i>s.penkevich wrote: "Mike wrote: "Thanks. For a second there, when you mentioned the postwar thing, my blood ran cold and I reached with a trembling hand for the copyright page, afraid I was completely wrong. 1953. Phe..."</i><br /><br />I actually finished the book a few weeks ago, but struggled to write a review, as I usually do when I really like something. I have this impulse to try to do the book justice somehow, which of course I can never do, but I'm glad I could at least remind you of your love for Chandler. Your review helped me out too, in a different way, because I happened across it before I read the book. I didn't read your review in its entirety at that time, but I skimmed enough to get a sense of your enthusiasm and what you conveyed of the book's atmosphere. I'd already been planning to read it, but your review kind of nudged me along, reminded me that oh, yeah, a lot of people think this one is <i>awesome</i>.<br /><br />I'd say you're right that Marlowe seems like someone lingering on as the world is changing. Potter is like that too, and Ohls as well. I enjoyed his late-novel rant against gambling, and the complicity of state governments. He'd really love Fan Duel. Is your review the one that mentioned that Ohls used to smoke, and now just puts an unlit cigarette between his lips?<br /><br />On the other hand, even though he's getting older, Marlowe's detecting skills are still pretty sharp. It seemed to me that he'd often reached important conclusions well before bothering to inform the reader or any other character, which made it all the more dramatic when he would casually say something like, "well, of course he did it. Didn't you notice his untied shoelace?" I guess that's an old detective author's trick that must go back to at least Conan Doyle. <br /><br />If Marlowe really invests that much in Terry, as you say, that might help to explain <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[why he's so hard on the guy <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>.<br /><br />I suppose one reason I was surprised by Marlowe's strong sense of morality is that I was introduced to the character in an untraditional way, having watched the Altman movie well before I read this one, or even <i>The Big Sleep</i>. Now I see that Altman's Marlowe was, well, more Altman-ish and maybe more Gould-ish than Chandler-ish. Or maybe that character is supposed to be a 70s update, a Marlowe who's gotten to the point of not caring, even if the ending of the movie belies that, a little. My Goodreads friend Jon interviewed Gould (I tried to include the link here, but it won't let me for some reason- I'll send it in a PM if you're interested), and Jon made that point in the interview- that at the end of the day, it turns out Gould's Marlowe does care, even if he seems to take everything with a shrug. <br /><br />I think I'll give <i>Farewell, My Lovely</i> a shot pretty soon. I've been reading <i>8 Million Ways to Die</i> by Lawrence Block in an effort to scratch the detective/P.I. itch, and it's...not bad, but it's not Chandler. I haven't read much Pynchon, only <i>Lot 49</i> about a decade ago. I should give him another chance, and <i>Inherent Vice</i> does sound fun, given my newfound fondness for the hardboiled genre and its offshoots. I've seen the movie and found it kind of incomprehensible, but sometimes I can dig that, as I think they said in the 70s.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5409561703517888051" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

